{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600271/1930022001/0063.xml":{"full_text":"B-14\nJAPANESE BALLOT\nON MINSOTO RULE\nBitterly Fought Campaign\nCenters on Domestic\nEconomic Issues.:\nBr the Associated Press.\nTOKIO. February 20.\u2014Balloting open\ned throughout Japan early today In the\ngeneral election which will decide the\nfate of the present Minseito govern\nment. headed by Premier Yuko Hama\nguchi.\nThe prime minister dissolved the Im\nperial Parliament January 21 and ap\npealed to the electorate for a mandate\nto continue in office, for approval of its\nprogram of drastic national economy\nand of its recent restoration of the gold\nstandard.\nIn the last Parliament the opposition\nparty, the Seiyukai. had 237 seats of the\ntotal of 466, wPh the Minseito party\nholding only 173.\nIt was generally predicted that the\nMinseito would gain a substantial plu- j\nrality and possibly an absolute majority, j\n839 Are Contestants.\nA total of 839 candidates are con\ntesting for the offices. The Minseito\nparty had 355 candidates, the Seiyukai\n305. the Proletarian or Labor groups 95,\nwith 84 others divided among the in\ndependent parties. The latter have been\ndivided among themselves and are un-\nlikely to increase their bloc much above\nthe 7 seats held in the last House\nof Representatives. A few small parties j\nare likely to return from 1 to 4 mem- I\nbers, while among the large sprinkling\nof independent candidates from 20 to 30\nare usually elected.\nThe bitterly fought campaign has 1\nbeen concerned almost altogether with\ndomestic economic issues. The London j\nnaval conference was not mentioned in i\nthe platform of either major party. The\nMinseito defended its economic program\nand the return to gold payments as the\nonly sure road to stability and eventual\nprosperity. The Seiyukai charged that\nthe program had brought on unneces\nsary business depression and unemploy\nment and promised an early return of\nprosperity and jobs for all if it were\ngiven a mandate.\nBuddhists Are Entered.\nSmall but politically unimportant\ngroups, which nevertheless figured in\nthe contest, were the militant Bud\ndhists. who put up several Buddhist\npriests as candidates, and the prohibi\ntionists. who entered no candidate, but\nfought lustily against known drinkers\nand supported those who came out in\nfavor of further restrictions of the\nliquor traffic.\nWomen played an increasingly im\nportant part in the campaign.\nNearly 13,000,000 persons are eligible\nto vote and between 70 and 80 per cent\nof them were expected to exercise this\nright. Voting was by secret ballot.\nPremier Hamaguchi and six members\nof his cabinet were candidates for seats i\nin the Lower House.\nTAXI DffIVER SLAIN\nIN PITTSBURGH RIOT\nMotor Cycle Policeman Fires at\nSpeeding Car After Almost\nBeing Ban Down.\n\nBy the Associated Press.\nPITTSBURGH, February 20 \u2014William\nDreibhold, 24, a former taxi driver, was\nshot to death by a motor cycle police\nman during a taxi strike riot at the\nBaltimore Sc Ohio Railroad station here\nshortly before last midnight.\nCalx, driven by strikebreakers and\nguarded by deputy sheriffs, were stoned\nas they were about to leave the station,\naccording to the police. Motor cycle\npolicemen summoned to the scene said\na car in which Dreibhold was riding\nwith three companions sped from the\nstation during the attack and that\nMotor Ccycle Patrolman William Har\nrison fired one shot after the car had\nnarrowly escaped running him down\nand the driver had refused to complv\nwith his command to stop. Dreibhold\nwas seen to slump into the seat as\nthe car sped away.\nSaturday\nENDS THE FINAL SALE\nNOT FOR SIX MONTHS\nWILL ARTCRAFT HOLD\nANOTHER FINAL SALE\nAtour f -85\nSt B Formerly\nShop Only B 14.50 to 18.50\nEVERY SIZE IS INCLUDED\nBUT NOT IN EVERY STYLE.\nEARLY SHOPPING IS ADVISED.\nAt Both Shops\nAJSroup of Smart Footwear pgj\nj|\nA _ 1\nARTCRAFT\nI3llf/TR\u00abT I\n1101 CONNECTICUT AV<.\ni\n\n\u2022v\nA Tennis Beauty\nJP I >/*\u00a3,'\u2022\u25a0fek\nMISS CECELIE AUSSEM,\nWh\u00ab is not only one of the best of the\nwomen tennis players of Germany, but\nalso a prominent beauty of that coun\ntry. She is a familiar figure in inter\nnational tennis competition.\n\u2014P. A. Photos.\nFLOOD OF LOBBYISTS\nSEEN BY M\u2019MASTER\n\nSenator Tells of Activities of In\ndustries to Win Legislation\nin Congress.\n\n\"Lobbyists swarm Washington,\u201d Sen\nator McMaster, Republican, of South\nDakota told farmers of the country\nin an address over a network of the\nNational Broadcasting Co. yesterday.\nHe spoke under auspices of the Farm\ners\u2019 Union during the National Farm\nand Home hour.\n\"The influence of lobbyists is felt so\ncially as well as politically,\u201d the Sena\ntor said, \"and, while the story of their\nactivities is a sordid one, yet neverthe\nless their efforts have been crowned\nwith amazing success.\n\"Five years of experience in the Sen\nate have demonstrated how powerful\nindustrial organizations have become.\nTheir influence on national legislation\nis outstanding and, in my judgment,\nhas become a menace.\u201d\nSpeaking of the nomination of\nCharles Evans Hughes for Chief Jus\ntice, Senator McMaster said: \"The\nfight just waged in the United States\nSenate over the appointment of Chief\nJustice Hughes has undoubtedly, lh a\ngeneral way, been represented as a\nfight against an individual. Far-reach\ning economic questions were involved\nin that fight.\u201d\nElectric Project Revealed.\nROME. February 20 UP). \u2014Count Volpi\ndl Misurata, former Minister of finance,\ntoday told Premier Mussolini of the or\nganization of the European Electric\nCorporation for the development of\nelectric power in Europe under Italian\ncontrol and technical direction. The\ncount said American finance had con\ntributed largely to the issue of the cor\nporation\u2019s stock.\nittUiihck\n'a first in the\n4| HEARTS OF\nTHOSE WHO\nENTERTAIN\nTHE EVENING STAB. W